'''Arnold Lynch''' (3 June 1914 – 13 November 2004) was an English engineer, known for his work on an optical tape reader which was used in the construction of the [[Colossus computer|Colossus]], the first electronic computer. By 1944 ten Colossus computers were installed at [[Bletchley Park]] and used to read high-level (''fish'' or ''tunny'') German ciphers.

Lynch joined the [[Post Office Research Station]] in 1936, specialising in the measurement of the electrical and magnetic properties of materials. He retired in 1974, but continued to come to work at [[National Physical Laboratory, UK|NPL]] in the [[dielectric]] area of RF and microwave electromagnetism up to the year of his death.

The Maths and Technology Department at [[Dame Alice Owen's School]] was named after Lynch in thanks for his work during his time at the school and his success as a scientist.

