'''Nirmal Puwar''' is a senior lecturer at the department of [[Sociology]] at [[Goldsmiths, University of London|Goldsmiths University]] and Co-Director of Methods Lab<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gold.ac.uk/sociology/staff/puwar/|title=Nirmal Puwar BA MA PhD|work=Goldsmiths, University of London|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en}}</ref>. She is a member of the [[Feminist Review]] editorial collective since 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biography.omicsonline.org/united-kingdom/goldsmiths-university-of-london/nirmal-puwar-434823|title=Nirmal Puwar {{!}} Goldsmiths University of London {{!}} United Kingdom|website=OMICS International|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Puwar|first=Nirmal|date=2009|title=A Feminist Review roundtable on the (un) certainties of the routes of the collective and the journal|url=http://www.scielo.mec.pt/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&pid=S0874-55602009000100003&lng=pt&nrm=iso&tlng=en|journal=Ex aequo|issue=19|pages=23–32|issn=0874-5560}}</ref>.  Puwar has co-edited 17 Collections, including: Post-colonial Bourdieu; Orientalism and Fashion; Intimacy in Research; Live Methods and, South Asian Women in the Diaspora.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torch.ox.ac.uk/racism-body-academy-statues-and-classrooms|title=Racism in the Body of the Academy: Statues and Classrooms {{!}} TORCH|website=torch.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>

Puwar has written about and researches [[postcolonialism]]; institutions, race and gender & critical methodologies and has written two books; Space Invaders: race, gender and bodies out of place (2004),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://research.gold.ac.uk/2017/|title=Space Invaders: race, gender and bodies out of place|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>, in which she argues that that diversity is about perceptions of whiteness rather than how whiteness operates,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.artshub.com.au/education/news-article/opinions-and-analysis/professional-development/tania-canas/diversity-is-a-white-word-252910|title=Diversity is a white word|last=Canas|first=Tania|work=ArtsHub Australia|access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref> and ''Fashion and Orientalism (2003).''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://research.gold.ac.uk/634/|title=Fashion and Orientalism|date=2003|website=research.gold.ac.uk|others=Puwar, Nirmal, Bhatia, Nandi, Mast, J.|access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref> In 2007, she directed the film [http://www.darkmatter101.org/site/2007/03/12/coventry-ritz-cinema/ Coventry Ritz] which emphasizes "the haunting remnants of emptied out architecture and unused space."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.darkmatter101.org/site/2007/03/12/coventry-ritz-cinema/|title=Coventry Ritz Cinema [video] {{!}} darkmatter Journal|website=www.darkmatter101.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> 

